    },
    {
      "id": "ad5e8dd9b560d2bcaf3421e7377af2e73679692f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 931,
        "name": "Timothy Day",
        "email": "timday@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "timday"
      },
      "date": "2025-04-26 17:07:24.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nHow does checking against the uapi work if you build a kernel without fscrypt support?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "7536407223c896b251d8183cd692058de89b40bb",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 931,
        "name": "Timothy Day",
        "email": "timday@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "timday"
      },
      "date": "2025-04-26 17:08:19.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nIn other words, would this give a false positive when building against a kernel with no fscrypt support?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "82facee09edaea4ff3420ddf0cc65687a5b889d9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2025-04-28 12:47:48.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nping",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "657131a18d7dcaec42b7c2e0e935d48c25f727e8",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 655,
        "name": "Arshad Hussain",
        "email": "arshad.hussain@aeoncomputing.com",
        "username": "arshad512"
      },
      "date": "2025-05-03 12:13:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1\n\n(2 comments)",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "738be41c2b70915772c76fc63b1e72a161436964",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 931,
        "name": "Timothy Day",
        "email": "timday@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "timday"
      },
      "date": "2025-05-06 18:52:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1\n\nLooking at the kernel source, it seems like this test would return \"yes\" regardless of whether CONFIG_FS_ENCRYPTION is true?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "edd774025b4885b90f9458b85e42dc9b38f8fc5a",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2025-05-08 15:46:08.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2:\n\nIf fscrypt in the kernel is not enabled then Lustre needs to turn on its own llcrypt version. \n\nHAVE_LUSTRE_CRYPTO tells us if the kernel supports the fscrypt API at a mature enough level. RHEL8 has a fscrypt version but its not mature enough which is why we have HAVE_LUSTRE_CRYPTO test.\n\nLooking at the test:\n\nif enable_crypto is in-kernel (use native) then test if fscrypt API is mature enough. If its not then we look at has_is_encrypted which tell us we are 4.14+ kernel which is enough for llcryptfs to work. For the native client, which only builds the utilities, we are interested if the kernel supports a mature fscrypt API so the user land tools build correctly. If the native kernel disabled fscrypt then the tools when run would just fail which is fine. Maybe we can harden it more with testing the connect_flags in the tools for test_dummy_encryption?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "d241d41c8762d3dee69e83437a7e2a7079cadb3b",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 931,
        "name": "Timothy Day",
        "email": "timday@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "timday"
      },
      "date": "2025-05-10 16:52:01.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 2: Code-Review+1\n\n> Patch Set 2:\n> \n> If fscrypt in the kernel is not enabled then Lustre needs to turn on its own llcrypt version. \n> \n> HAVE_LUSTRE_CRYPTO tells us if the kernel supports the fscrypt API at a mature enough level. RHEL8 has a fscrypt version but its not mature enough which is why we have HAVE_LUSTRE_CRYPTO test.\n> \n> Looking at the test:\n> \n> if enable_crypto is in-kernel (use native) then test if fscrypt API is mature enough. If its not then we look at has_is_encrypted which tell us we are 4.14+ kernel which is enough for llcryptfs to work. For the native client, which only builds the utilities, we are interested if the kernel supports a mature fscrypt API so the user land tools build correctly. If the native kernel disabled fscrypt then the tools when run would just fail which is fine. Maybe we can harden it more with testing the connect_flags in the tools for test_dummy_encryption?\n\nI see what you're doing now. I missed that this is in-kernel crypto vs. Lustre crypto. Thanks for the explanation.\n\nFor the userland tools, I think we should always build full support regardless of what the kernel is doing. Then probe the kernel for feature support at runtime.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 2
    },
    {
      "id": "a090771995016632306717c9a19bdfbd3e6658c2",
